us === expectedStatus`.\n- `owner_tasks` filtered by request_id must have exactly 4 entries, with `owner_group` in order `[\"Operations\",\"Support\",\"Finance\",\"Logistics\"]`, and **every** task must have truthy `title`, truthy `due_at`, and `status === \"open\"`.\n- `customer_messages` must contain at least one with matching `request_id` and a truthy `body`.\n- `audit_events` must contain at least one with matching `request_id` and truthy `customer_visible`.\n\n## 5. Schema / Migration / SQL — FULL CONTENTS\n\n`migrations/001_table_contract.sql` defines 12 tables. Note: all columns are `text` and the 4 output tables (`workflow_state`, `owner_tasks`, `audit_events`, `customer_messages`) are declared with a single `value text` column in SQL, but in the actual JSON fixture they're empty arrays `[]` that the test expects to be filled with **structured objects** (not a scalar `value`). The SQL is a nominal contract only; the real shape is driven by `portal-view.mjs` + the test. The 8 seeded tables are: `benchmark_fixture`, `accounts`, `account_contracts`, `contacts`, `workflow_requests`, `workflow_request_owner_groups`, `workflow_request_risk_signals`, `activities`.\n\n`schema/schema.md` and `schema/access-paths.md` describe the read/write paths:\n- **Read**: load workflow request → reconstruct account context → resolve owner groups + risk signals → persist state/tasks/message/audit → render portal projection.\n- **Write**: persist one workflow state, all owner tasks, one customer-safe message, one customer-visible audit event.\n\n## 6. Fixture / Seed Data — `data/tables.json`\n\nIn-memory \"tables\" as JSON arrays. Structure and sample contents:\n- `benchmark_fixture` (1 row): `{fixture_version, suite_id, task_id, generated_at}`.\n- `accounts` (1 row): `{account_id:\"acct-split-ship\", name:\"Order Account 1\", tier:\"enterprise\", region:\"NA\"}`.\n- `account_contracts` (1 row): `{contract_id, account_id, renewal_date:\"2026-09-30\", arr_cents:7200000, support_plan